Split this into two reviewable patches.

Phase 1 is preparatory refactoring only. Keep `acceptRow` returning `boolean`, keep the push side effect where it is, and only decompose the nested conditionals into named checks plus a single validation path. That matches the refactoring guidance: remove the structural friction first, without smuggling in the feature.

```ts
function hasFieldCount(row: string[]): boolean {
  return row.length === 4;
}

function hasId(row: string[]): boolean {
  return row[0] !== "";
}

function hasSupportedKind(row: string[]): boolean {
  return row[1] === "person" || row[1] === "company";
}

function hasNumericScore(row: string[]): boolean {
  return /^\d+$/.test(row[2]);
}

function hasSupportedStatus(row: string[]): boolean {
  return row[3] === "active" || row[3] === "inactive";
}

function isAcceptableRow(row: string[]): boolean {
  if (!hasFieldCount(row)) return false;
  if (!hasId(row)) return false;
  if (!hasSupportedKind(row)) return false;
  if (!hasNumericScore(row)) return false;
  if (!hasSupportedStatus(row)) return false;
  return true;
}

export function acceptRow(row: string[]): boolean {
  if (!isAcceptableRow(row)) {
    return false;
  }

  acceptedRows.push({
    id: row[0],
    kind: row[1],
    score: Number(row[2]),
    status: row[3],
  });

  return true;
}
```

Phase-1 tests: ideally none change if the current suite already characterizes behavior. If coverage is incomplete, only add characterization tests that prove the old `true`/`false` contract and push/no-push behavior.

Phase 2 is the behavior change. Introduce explicit row meaning, convert validation into a typed internal result, and make `acceptRow` return the new `AcceptanceResult`. Keep the boundary checks deliberately aligned with the current rules so the only product change is the rejection reason.

```ts
type RowKind = "person" | "company";
type RowStatus = "active" | "inactive";
type RejectionReason =
  | "field-count"
  | "missing-id"
  | "kind"
  | "score"
  | "status";

type AcceptanceResult =
  | { accepted: true }
  | { accepted: false; reason: RejectionReason };

type ParsedRow = {
  id: string;
  kind: RowKind;
  score: number;
  status: RowStatus;
};

type ValidationResult =
  | { ok: true; value: ParsedRow }
  | { ok: false; reason: RejectionReason };

function validateRow(row: string[]): ValidationResult {
  if (row.length !== 4) {
    return { ok: false, reason: "field-count" };
  }

  const [id, kind, scoreText, status] = row;

  if (id === "") {
    return { ok: false, reason: "missing-id" };
  }

  if (kind !== "person" && kind !== "company") {
    return { ok: false, reason: "kind" };
  }

  if (!/^\d+$/.test(scoreText)) {
    return { ok: false, reason: "score" };
  }

  if (status !== "active" && status !== "inactive") {
    return { ok: false, reason: "status" };
  }

  return {
    ok: true,
    value: {
      id,
      kind,
      score: Number(scoreText),
      status,
    },
  };
}

export function acceptRow(row: string[]): AcceptanceResult {
  const validation = validateRow(row);
  if (!validation.ok) {
    return { accepted: false, reason: validation.reason };
  }

  acceptedRows.push(validation.value);
  return { accepted: true };
}
```

Phase-2 tests should cover:
- accepts a valid row, returns `{ accepted: true }`, and pushes the parsed object
- rejects wrong field count with `"field-count"`
- rejects empty id with `"missing-id"`
- rejects unsupported kind with `"kind"`
- rejects non-digit score with `"score"`
- rejects unsupported status with `"status"`
- for each rejection case, `acceptedRows` is unchanged

That keeps the two intents clean:
1. preparatory refactor: flatten and name the validation logic, no observable behavior change
2. feature change: switch the public contract from boolean rejection to typed rejection reasons

